<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Learn IDOR | VulnLab</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/style.css">
</head>

<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h1>🔐 VulnLab</h1>
        <h2>📚 Understanding IDOR</h2>

        <!-- ─── What is IDOR ─────────────────────────────── -->
        <div class="learn-card">
            <h3>What is IDOR?</h3>
            <p>
                <strong>Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR)</strong> is a vulnerability that occurs
                when an application exposes internal object references (like database IDs) without
                verifying if the requesting user has permission to access that object.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── Root Cause ───────────────────────────────── -->
        <div class="learn-card">
            <h3>Root Cause</h3>
            <p>The server only asks <strong>"Does this order exist?"</strong> but never asks <strong>"Does this order
                    belong to YOU?"</strong></p>
            <div class="code-block">
                <p>// ❌ Vulnerable Code</p>
                <p>const order = db.prepare('SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id = ?').get(orderId);</p>
                <p>res.render('order', { order });</p>
                <br />
                <p>// ✅ Secure Code</p>
                <p>if (order.user_id !== req.session.user_id) {"{"} </p>
                <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;return res.status(403).send('Forbidden');</p>
                <p>{"}"}</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── Authentication vs Authorization ─────────── -->
        <div class="learn-card">
            <h3>Authentication vs Authorization</h3>
            <p><strong>Authentication</strong> — Verifies WHO you are. (Login system)</p>
            <p><strong>Authorization</strong> — Verifies WHAT you are allowed to access.</p>
            <br />
            <p>IDOR is an <strong>authorization failure</strong> — the app knows who you are but doesn't check what you
                can access.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── Exploit Steps ────────────────────────────── -->
        <div class="learn-card">
            <h3>How to Exploit IDOR in this Lab</h3>
            <p>1. Login as <strong>alice</strong> / alice123</p>
            <p>2. View your own order at <code>/orders/1</code></p>
            <p>3. Change the URL to <code>/orders/4</code></p>
            <p>4. You can now see Bob's order — data breach!</p>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── Real World Impact ────────────────────────── -->
        <div class="learn-card">
            <h3>Real World Impact</h3>
            <p>IDOR vulnerabilities have been found in major platforms:</p>
            <br />
            <p>🔴 <strong>Facebook</strong> — Researcher could delete anyone's photos by changing photo ID</p>
            <p>🔴 <strong>Uber</strong> — Changing user ID in API exposed trip history and personal data</p>
            <p>🔴 <strong>Banking Apps</strong> — Changing account ID exposed other users' bank statements</p>
        </div>

        <!-- ─── The Fix ───────────────────────────────────── -->
        <div class="learn-card">
            <h3>The Fix</h3>
            <p>Always verify ownership before returning any object:</p>
            <div class="code-block">
                <p>const order = db.prepare('SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id = ?').get(orderId);</p>
                <br />
                <p>// Always add this check!</p>
                <p>if (order.user_id !== req.session.user_id) {"{"} </p>
                <p>&nbsp;&nbsp;return res.status(403).send('Forbidden');</p>
                <p>{"}"}</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <br />
        <a href="/dashboard">← Back to Dashboard</a>
    </div>
</body>

</html>